Then we need to show `List.foldl afunc [] (head :: tail) = []`.

Let's look at the definition of `List.foldl`.
`List.foldl f acc (x :: xs) = f acc x :: List.foldl f (f acc x) xs`
`List.foldl f acc [] = acc`

So `List.foldl afunc [] (head :: tail)` becomes:
`afunc [] head :: List.foldl afunc (afunc [] head) tail`

We need to show this equals `[]`.

From the definition of `afunc`:
`fun prev x => if h_is : index₁ = x.2 then prev ++ [x] else prev`
So `afunc [] head` becomes:
`if index₁ = head.2 then [] ++ [head] else []`
This simplifies to:
`if index₁ = head.2 then [head] else []`

Now, `List.foldl afunc (afunc [] head) tail` becomes:
`List.foldl afunc (afunc [] head) tail`

If `afunc [] head` is non-empty (i.e., `index₁ = head.2`), then `List.foldl afunc (afunc [] head) tail` will be non-empty.
But we have `h_neg : ¬∃ location ∈ head :: tail, location.2 = index₁`.
This means `index₁ ≠ head.2`.
Therefore `afunc [] head` must be `[]`.
So `List.foldl afunc [] (head :: tail)` becomes `List.foldl afunc [] tail`.
And by the induction hypothesis `ind_hyp`, this is `[]` if `¬∃ location ∈ tail, location.2 = index₁`.
But `h_neg` implies `¬∃ location ∈ tail, location.2 = index₁`.
So the whole expression is `[]`.

This reasoning can be formalized in Lean.

