The fix involves replacing the `sorry` tactics with appropriate reasoning. When `index₁ = head₂.2`, the goal is `List.foldl afunc (List.foldl afunc [] [head₂]) tail₂ = []`. This is true because `List.foldl afunc [] [head₂]` is `[ (head₂.1, head₂.2) ]` (if `head₂.2` matches `index₁`), and then `List.foldl afunc [ (head₂.1, head₂.2) ] tail₂` will be `[ (head₂.1, head₂.2) ]` if `tail₂` is empty, or will process `tail₂` elements. However, the structure of `afunc` means that if `index₁` matches `head₂.2`, then `(head₂.1, head₂.2)` is added to the list if `head₂.2` is the index of the element in `allChildren`. The proof needs to establish that this element is not in `allChildren` if `List.foldl afunc [] tail₂ = []`.

The corrected code uses a more direct approach for `afunc_monotone`:
